# ClearML Training on GPU Runners

## Primary worker: **bs3** (current focus)

**Treat bs3 as the only ClearML GPU target for now.** It has the **fastest GPU** in the fleet (RTX 5070 Ti, 16 GB VRAM). Docs, `.env` examples, and pipeline enqueueing should assume **`gpu_bs3`** until multi-host tuning is intentional.

| Item | Value |
|------|--------|
| **Host** | bs3 (Tailscale / MagicDNS) |
| **ClearML queue** | `gpu_bs3` |
| **GPU** | NVIDIA RTX 5070 Ti, 16 GB VRAM |
| **Worker label** | `bs3:gpu0` (see agent logs) |
| **SSH (ops)** | `ssh root@100.98.15.96` (Tailscale; use your allowed user if policy differs) |
| **Systemd agent** | `clearml-agent-gpu.service` |
| **MinIO S3 API** | Same tailnet: `bs3:9000` ŌåÆ use `http://bs3:9000` / `MINIO_ENDPOINT=bs3:9000` (not `s3.multiagent.vision`) |
| **Co-located** | MinIO and ClearML agent on bs3 keeps dataset I/O and training on the fast GPU without crossing the public edge |

### Standard: run the whole pipeline on bs3

Set **all** pipeline queues to `gpu_bs3` in `model_train/.env` so controller, data prep, train, export, and report execute on the same worker:

```bash
PIPELINE_EXECUTION_QUEUE=gpu_bs3
PIPELINE_DATA_PREP_QUEUE=gpu_bs3
PIPELINE_MODEL_TRAIN_QUEUE=gpu_bs3
PIPELINE_EXPORT_TEST_QUEUE=gpu_bs3
PIPELINE_REPORT_QUEUE=gpu_bs3
```

Single-task scripts (e.g. `train_boards_clearml.py`) should use `execute_remotely(queue_name="gpu_bs3", ...)`.

**Later:** Spread steps across bs2 / rg* (VeraŌĆÖs defaults in `pipeline.py` use `gpu_bs2`, `gpu_rg1`, etc.). That is **out of scope** until you explicitly want load distribution; update env vars and re-test MinIO reachability from each host.

